http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/15/world/asia/15cnd-pakista.html	Suicide Bombing Kills at Least 22 in Pakistan - New York Times Suicide Bombing Kills at Least 22 in Pakistan Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 15, 2007 PESHAWAR, May 15 — Twenty-two people were killed and 30 wounded here today when a suicide bomber struck a crowded restaurant in a busy part of the old city, police and hospital officials said. The bomb exploded at about 12:55 p.m. at the Marhaba Restaurant, which is on the ground floor of a four-story building opposite the historic Mohabat Khan mosque. The powerful explosion seriously damaged the hotel and caused damage to nearby shops and buildings. All that was left of the restaurant were shattered window panes and twisted fans hanging from the ceiling. It was not clear why the bomber targeted the restaurant, which is frequented by local residents who work in a nearby jewelry market and at the city’s biggest teaching hospital. But witnesses and police said the restaurant was owned by an Uzbek of Afghan origin who was affiliated with former Uzbek warlord Abdur Rashid Dostum. Posters of Mr. Dostrum adorned the walls of the restaurant. The owner of the restaurant, his brother and his son died in the explosion. “It definitely was a suicide bombing,” chief investigator, Fayaz Toru, told Dawn, an English-language newspaper in Karachi. He added that the initial investigation indicated the incident fit the pattern of similar suicide bombings in the area. News services reported that the provincial police chief, Sharif Virk, said he had recovered a suicide note written in an Afghan variant of Persian called Dari, as well as in Pashto, warning that those who spied for the United States face a similar fate. But Mr. Virk and other police investigators distanced themselves from those reports. Qazi Jamilur Rehman, head of the investigating team, denied that a suicide note had been recovered. “We are yet to reach any conclusion, but this can be said, that it was in reaction to the prevalent geo-political scenario in the region,” Mr. Virk told Dawn. Investigators and security officiald also denied news service reports that the suicide bombing may have been linked to the arrest of a close relative of Mullah Dadullah days before Mr. Dadullah was killed in the southwestern Helmand province in Afghanistan. Mr. Dadullah, probably the ’s foremost operational commander, was killed in a joint operation by Afghan security forces, American forces and Law Minister Malik Zafar Azam said the explosion could have been related to other bombings in the tribal regions and the presence of U.S. troops in Body parts could be seen scattered at the scene of today’s attack, and most of the bodies were charred. Victims were rushed to the nearby Lady Reading Hospital, about 200 meters from the spot, and the government declared an emergency. Two women and a child were among those killed. Mr. Toru said that the police found nuts and bolts, often used in suicide explosions, at the scene. “I was in the kitchen when I heard a big explosion and fell unconscious,” said Muslim Shah, a cook at the restaurant, who was injured. Chief Minister Akram Khan Durrani condemned the incident and announced that the families of those killed an injured would receive financial compensation. The explosion was the second recent suicide bombing in the area. On April 28, 32 people were killed when a suicide bomber struck a rally during an address by Interior Minister Aftab Ahmad Khan Sherpao in his town of Charsadda, northeast of Peshawar. On January 27, 15 people were killed, among them senior police officers, when a suicide bomber blew himself up in the heart of Peshawar City. More Articles in International &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. More Articles in International &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
