http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/15/world/middleeast/15cnd-gaza.html?ex=1336881600&en=f77f23bbbf455bcd&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	At Least 7 Killed in Gaza Fighting - New York Times At Least 7 Killed in Gaza Fighting Mahmud Hams/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images A Palestinian child today in front of the bodies of slain Fatah security officers at the morgue in the Deir el-Balah hospital in the Gaza Strip. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 15, 2007 NAHAL OZ, Israel, May 15 &#151; Fighters from the military wing of , one of the two main Palestinian political factions, attacked security forces loyal to the rival Fatah faction at a location in Gaza near the border with Israel today, killing nine people, according to Fatah officials. Skip to next paragraph Mahmud Hams/Agence France-Presse — Getty Images Palestinians today carrying the body of a security force member into the morgue in the Deir el-Balah hospital in the Gaza Strip. The clashes extended an outbreak of factional violence to a third day, threatening the survival of the two-month-old &#8220;unity&#8221; government of the Palestinian Authority, the result of a power-sharing agreement between Hamas and Fatah. The attack by Hamas fighters on the Presidential Guard, which is loyal to the Palestinian president, of Fatah, seemed to be a direct challenge to his authority. Raising the stakes further, the Hamas military wing said that it had fired the Qassam rockets that hit the Israeli border town of Sderot this evening, wounding several civilians, one seriously. The Palestinian information minister, Mustafa Barghouti, warned that if the unity government collapses, the whole Palestinian Authority could go down with it. Israeli troops fired today at two armed Palestinians who were spotted close to the border fence opposite Nahal Oz, a kibbutz that abuts the Gaza Strip, killing one of the two, an army spokeswoman said. Local news reports identified the two as members of the Presidential Guard who were fleeing the Hamas attack at the Karni commercial border crossing, which is nearby. At least one other Palestinian was killed in factional violence in Gaza City today, bringing the death toll to about 20 since the clashes resumed on Sunday after three months of relative calm. Israeli tanks lined up on the Israeli side of the border this morning while fierce gun battles raged among the Palestinian forces on the other side, but the tanks had drawn back by early afternoon. In the evening, a barrage of Qassam rockets fired from Gaza struck Sderot, hitting a house and a school, army officials said. According to Israel Radio, Hamas said the rockets were meant to commemorate Nakba Day, when Palestinians mark the anniversary of what they call the &#8220;catastrophe&#8221; of the establishment of the State of Israel in 1948. During the day, the Prime Minister of Israel, , met with King Abdullah of Jordan in the port city of Aqaba. David Baker, an official in Mr. Olmert&#8217;s office, said the leaders had a &#8220;warm and productive meeting, in which they discussed ways of promoting the Israeli-Palestinian process.&#8221; Mr. Baker said the leaders also discussed ways of shoring up the position of Mr. Abbas and other relative moderates in the Palestinian Authority. But the intensity of today&#8217;s violence in Gaza raised serious doubts about the viability of the joint government, and about the future of the Palestinian Authority as a whole. One of the main purposes of the power-sharing agreement was to stop factional violence that was threatening to spiral into civil war. &#8220;If this government falls, it means the collapse of the Palestinian Authority, and with it, the end of all agreements,&#8221; said Mr. Barghouti, the government spokesman. Speaking by telephone from Ramallah, he said that President Abbas had told the Palestinian cabinet on Monday night, &#8220;This is my government, and if it falls, I will fall with it.&#8221; The attack on the Fatah-aligned forces guarding the Karni crossing was the most audacious show of force by Hamas since the violence restarted, and it ratcheted up the hostility level between the warring factions. A spokesman for Hamas&#8217;s police force, Islam Shahwan, said that today&#8217;s violence started with the killing of Ibrahim Maniah, 45, a member of the Hamas-linked Qassam Brigade militia, by members of the Fatah-linked Presidential Guard in the Gaza neighborhood of Sajaiya, near the Karni crossing. Mr. Shahwan called the killing an assasination; Fatah officials denied that, and said Mr. Maniah was killed during street clashes. Mr. Abbas&#8217;s Presidential Guard is responsible for security at the Karni crossing. A spokesman for the Presidential Guard, Wael Dahab, said that Hamas raided a security position there, firing guns and rocket-propelled grenades. Three jeeps from the pro-Fatah National Security Forces drove toward Karni to provide backup to the Presidential Guard, but one of the vehicles overturned on the road, Fatah spokesmen said. Tawfiq Abu Houssa, a Fatah security official, said that Qassam Brigade members then went up to the overturned jeep and killed the seven men inside, shooting them &#8220;in cold blood, at close range.&#8221; He said their weapons were stolen. A Hamas spokesman, Fawzi Barhoum, said that the &#8220;Fatah accusations came without any investigation.&#8221; Earlier, Hamas spokesmen said Israel was to blame for the deaths of the National Security Force members, saying they were killed by a tank shell fired from across the border that struck the jeep. But the Israeli army spokeswoman denied that any shells had been fired. The Palestinian information minister, Mr. Barghouti, a political independent, said that the day&#8217;s events were still under investigation, and that &#8220;both sides&#8221; were responsible for the violence. By the afternoon, Gaza was mostly quiet, though sporadic bursts of gunfire could be heard. Across the border in the Nahal Oz kibbutz, tractors worked to harvest a carrot crop until a Qassam rocket landed in an open field at about 3 p.m., the first rocket to be fired today, the Israeli army said. Inside Gaza the atmosphere remained tense. Most people stayed at home, stores were closed, and gunmen from Hamas or Fatah took up positions in taller buildings in Gaza City, while Egyptian officials worked in earnest to try to mediate and restore calm. &#8220;With every new confrontation, the ability of the leaders to control their people on the ground is reduced,&#8221; said Mr. Barghouti. &#8220;There are certain people who don&#8217;t want calm.&#8221; Taghreed El-Khodary contributed reporting from Gaza City. More Articles in International &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Jordan&#8217;s King Calls Off Visit to the West Bank Hamas-Fatah Gunfight Worsens Factional Strife in Gaza Clash at U.N.-Run Gaza School Kills One and Wounds 6 World Briefing | Middle East: Gaza: Demands For BBC Journalist Rejected More Articles in International &#x00bb; A Giant Takes On Physics&#8217; Biggest Questions An Amputee Sprinter: Is He Disabled or Too-Abled? Napa Valley? Bordeaux? No, but Still Wine Country The Greatest Mystery: Making a Best Seller Books: Doctors Who Wield the Pen to Heal the Profession Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Sex, Drugs and Updating Your Blog The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Basics: In Hive or Castle, Duty Without Power Development Rises on St. Louis Area Flood Plains Go to Complete List » Atomic Agency Concludes Iran Is Stepping Up Nuclear Work Ground Zero Illnesses Clouding Giuliani's Legacy Sex, Drugs and Updating Your Blog Is It the Woman Thing, or Is It Katie Couric? Billions in Oil Missing in Iraq, U.S. Study Finds The Flight From Iraq In a New Role, Senator Clinton's Strategist in Chief Religious Groups Granted Millions for Pet Projects Obama Says He'd Roll Back Tax Cuts for the Wealthiest Army Career Behind Him, General Speaks Out on Iraq Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
