rding the Karni crossing was the most audacious show of force by Hamas since the violence restarted, and it ratcheted up the hostility level between the warring factions. A spokesman for Hamas&#8217;s police force, Islam Shahwan, said that today&#8217;s violence started with the killing of Ibrahim Maniah, 45, a member of the Hamas-linked Qassam Brigade militia, by members of the Fatah-linked Presidential Guard in the Gaza neighborhood of Sajaiya, near the Karni crossing. Mr. Shahwan called the killing an assasination; Fatah officials denied that, and said Mr. Maniah was killed during street clashes. Mr. Abbas&#8217;s Presidential Guard is responsible for security at the Karni crossing. A spokesman for the Presidential Guard, Wael Dahab, said that Hamas raided a security position there, firing guns and rocket-propelled grenades. Three jeeps from the pro-Fatah National Security Forces drove toward Karni to provide backup to the Presidential Guard, but one of the vehicles overturned on the road, Fatah spokesmen said. Tawfiq Abu Houssa, a Fatah security official, said that Qassam Brigade members then went up to the overturned jeep and killed the seven men inside, shooting them &#8220;in cold blood, at close range.&#8221; He said their weapons were stolen. A Hamas spokesman, Fawzi Barhoum, said that the &#8220;Fatah accusations came without any investigation.&#8221; Earlier, Hamas spokesmen said Israel was to blame for the deaths of the National Security Force members, saying they were killed by a tank shell fired from across the border that struck the jeep. But the Israeli army spokeswoman denied that any shells had been fired. The Palestinian information minister, Mr. Barghouti, a political independent, said that the day&#8217;s events were still under investigation, and that &#8220;both sides&#8221; were responsible for the violence. By the afternoon, Gaza was mostly quiet, though sporadic bursts of gunfire could be heard. Across the border in the Nahal Oz kibbutz, tractors worked to harvest a carrot crop until a Qassam rocket landed in an open field at about 3 p.m., the first rocket to be fired today, the Israeli army said. Inside Gaza the atmosphere remained tense. Most people stayed at home, stores were closed, and gunmen from Hamas or Fatah took up positions in taller buildings in Gaza City, while Egyptian officials worked in earnest to try to mediate and restore calm. &#8220;With every new confrontation, the ability of the leaders to control their people on the ground is reduced,&#8221; said Mr. Barghouti. &#8220;There are certain people who don&#8217;t want calm.&#8221; Taghreed El-Khodary contributed reporting from Gaza City. More Articles in International &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Jordan&#8217;s King Calls Off Visit to the West Bank Hamas-Fatah Gunfight Worsens Factional Strife in Gaza Clash at U.N.-Run Gaza School Kills One and Wounds 6 World Briefing | Middle East: Gaza: Demands For BBC Journalist Rejected More Articles in International &#x00bb; A Giant Takes On Physics&#8217; Biggest Questions An Amputee Sprinter: Is He Disabled or Too-Abled? Napa Valley? Bordeaux? No, but Still Wine Country The Greatest Mystery: Making a Best Seller Books: Doctors Who Wield the Pen to Heal the Profession Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Sex, Drugs and Updating Your Blog The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Basics: In Hive or Castle, Duty Without Power Gonzales Pressed Ailing Ashcroft on Spy Plan, Aide Says Go to Complete List » Atomic Agency Concludes Iran Is Stepping Up Nuclear Work Ground Zero Illnesses Clouding Giuliani's Legacy Sex, Drugs and Updating Your Blog Is It the Woman Thing, or Is It Katie Couric? Billions in Oil Missing in Iraq, U.S. Study Finds The Fli